social_posts.post_text: A quick phone edit on yesterdays sunny drive to a hot spring after 5 days of skiing.
A magical place where the only stress I could find came from knowing we’d have to leave.

While out to the most incredible seafood meal in Coco Beach, I asked the waiter what beach we should go and check out. 

After the most harrowing 25 min drive I’ve ever done we arrived at this gorgeous spot, with tide pools as far as we could see. I snapped this one of Megan walking like The Dude in the dream sequence of The Big Lebowski, and called it a successful afternoon. 

Canon Eos 1N | Kodak Gold 200

Between the downpour of rain and the cloud of mist coming off of these thundering falls, I’m genuinely amazed that I managed to get any photos without destroying any of my gear. 

Canon Eos1N | Kodak Portra 400
Proud lil hiker ➡️ wiped pup.
I always seem to have to hike down from this spot in the dark, but at least it’s always been after spectacular sunsets.

The only backpacking trip we got in last year. That number needs to increase dramatically if warm weather ever decides to come around. 

Canon Eos 1N | Kodak Portra 400

I played around with the underwater film camera quite a bit while in Costa Rica. Most of the photos were comically bad, some were pleasant surprises, and then there was this one—which is in no way underwater—that is so much fun and makes me happy. So goes the film shooting life. 

Nikonos V | Cinestill 400

The license plate on our rental car got stolen at some point on our trip—probably while we were at this beach—which turned into a fun situation when we returned the car. 

It was maybe probably still with the visit…maybe. 

Canon Eos 1N | Kodak Portra 400

Quick dip in a waterfall pool right before soaking in some hot springs—this was an incredible day. 

Nikonos V | Kodak Portra 400
View from the hanging bridge.
Some family portraits with a nice dark chocolate reward at the end of a long fall hike.

This was my first time shooting @cinestillfilm in 120 format and when I first saw the scans from @indiefilmlab, I thought the color palate was a little bit jarring. When I got to these photos, however, I was immediately so pleased as the colors reminded me so much of the digital edit that I did when I photographed this place in 2018. I was really hoping that the Cinestill 400d would have this effect, and am so happy that it seems like it will always have a certain use case for me. 

More scenes from this roll will be coming right up!

Pentax 6x7 | Pentax 105mm f2.4 | Cinestill 400d

Sights of Fairfield, ID. 

Pentax 6x7 | Pentax 105mm F2.4 | Cinestill 400d

I’ve wanted to drive through the north entrance of Yellowstone in the winter for a very long time. It’s a pretty long detour, and the road conditions can be horrendous, but seeing the geysers, bison, elk, and pronghorn with the snowy backdrop was spectacular. 

Pentax 6x7 | Pentax 105mm F2.4 | Kodak Portra 400

I decided to change up my skiing program, this year. 

After a horrible snow year at our local hill, I got the itch to get back to big mountain skiing. Looking at the various pass options, I settled on the little-discussed Mountain Collective Pass (@collectivepass). 

This is not an ad, but since I had a hard time finding information about the pass when I was looking at my options, I figured I’d write about my thoughts on my year with the pass—hint: if you’re in the Intermountain West and don’t mind traveling to different hills, the value is incredible. 

Nikonos V | Nikkor 35mm F2.5 | Kodak Gold 200
Costa Rica paddle.

Waterfall swim from Costa Rica.
Sundown in the Sawtooths at 3 focal lengths.

My ‘gramming is always been anything but Insta. I just don’t edit that way. I like getting space from my photos before working on any edits. 

For instance, these were from a trip in September of 2021, where I met @manbythesea in the Tetons for a road trip through Grand Teton and Yellowstone. Years later, I’m just getting the separation from these frames to really finalize my edits while John is en route to make this area his new home for the summer. 

The image of me was snapped by John on my trusty Pentax 6x7—he got to feel the shutter clunk! 

Pentax 6x7 | Pentax 55mm F4 | Kodak Portra 160

The scans that I got back were so far from what I was expecting that I just avoided them for a good long while, but now that I’ve got some distance from this evening shooting with beautiful golden light, the film photos have a really textured look that I’ve come around on.

This past spring, we headed out to the remote northwest corner of Nevada in partnership with @TravelNevada. Traveling in and around the Sheldon National Wildlife Refuge, we got the chance to camp in a #DarkSkySanctuary, relax in a warm spring, and explore one of the most dramatic canyons I have ever hiked in. We even stopped by @royalpeacockopalmines, where Megan got to put that Geology degree to good use while hunting for opals. This trip was another exercise in appreciating the limitless beauty hidden away from the beaten path in Nevada. 
#travelnevada #thatnevadalife

My schedule may have finally cleared up enough to let me run out to the mountains, this summer. 

I’m sure nobody wants to hear me complain about how busy I’ve been, but I’ve been like…super busy. It’s been impossible to get outside, plus I’m a wuss and am not handling the triple-digit weather well. 

Anywho, hoping to see these beautiful peaks very soon!

The whole family piled into the truck and headed into the northwest corner of Nevada this past spring as part of a partnership with @TravelNevada. This region had been a blank spot on the map that I had driven past countless times. 

Within close proximity to the northeastern entry point of the Sheldon National Wildlife Refuge area, we experienced pristine warm spring waters, a truly breathtaking gorge, and an opal mine where visitors can hunt for opals in a family-owned mine that has produced world-class specimens for five generations. After our first night, we needed to work our way westward, but this region proved to be a difficult one to leave. 

#travelnevada #thatnevadalife
Campsite hangs last summer.

#35mm from the Tetons. 

Contax G1 | Contax 45mm F2 | Kodak Portra 400

When @TravelNevada asked me to head out to the Massacre Rim Dark Sky Sanctuary to partake in some astrophotography, I was thrilled. From what I knew of the area, I knew the one thing that would not be an issue would be city lights. Unfortunately, the spring storms that doused most of the West this year found us and created an unforeseen barrier to getting photos of the clear night sky. However, this region that resides north of the @BlackRockDesert proved to be worth the trek even without the Milky Way views. 

As the 1,200 foot Massacre Rim came into view on our drive, we realized that it stretched as far as the eye could see. We found a road that traversed to the top of the impressive ridge line, where we could appreciate the sweeping view of the playas below the rim. When we were ready to set up camp, we found a suitable spot out on a playa and enjoyed one of the most vibrant sunsets I have ever seen while we ate a delicious meal. We ate in silence, marveling at the expansive solitude that Nevada delivered for us on that evening. We did not see another vehicle on this day. 

#travelnevada #thatnevadalife

Goodbye, Poppy. 

I still can’t say it without sobbing uncontrollably, but after being diagnosed with an aggressive cancer back in early June, Poppy’s magnificent life came to a gentle and loving end a week ago from today. We took her up to the mountains for one last round of family photos on the prior weekend, as I had seen the positive effects and memories created in offering end of life photos for some of my clients’ pups. This first frame will be the last new photo of our baby, Poppy, that I will ever share. It was a calm and beautiful evening, and she loved quietly breathing the mountain air. 

Poppy was fairly small for a Golden Retriever (she sometimes dipped below 50 pounds), but she seemed to have her own gravitational field. People would flock to her (once she caused a car accident from a driver ogling her), and she would light up any room she entered. The absence of her gigantic personality still feels jarring. 

I feel so privileged to have gotten to share her with so many people, whether it was the many friends she made along the way or all the nice people leaving nice comments for her on this platform. Work has taken Megan and I apart at a few junctures, and she was always there to be our best friend, to encourage us to be active, and to give endless unconditional love. It was said of Poppy that you were either “her best friend, or her new best friend.” What a wonderful way to be seen. 

She was the most wholly good thing I have known in my life, and I feel immeasurably lucky for getting to have such a special being be such a huge part of my life. Thank you to all of you for giving her so much love. You will never know how much she loved receiving it. 

Rest in peace my forever baby, Poppy Moose Brockway-Gambs, 

Your Papa
